# Fibonacco Frontend Rules

## Architecture Context
This is a Laravel + Inertia.js + React app with server-side rendering (SSR).
The frontend code runs in TWO environments: the browser AND Node.js (during SSR).
The app serves MULTIPLE brands from the same codebase — never hardcode brand-specific content.

## SSR Compatibility — CRITICAL

All frontend code may execute in Node.js where browser APIs don't exist.

```tsx
// ❌ CRASHES DURING SSR — window doesn't exist in Node.js
window.scrollTo(0, 0);
document.title = 'Hello';
localStorage.setItem('key', 'value');

// ✅ Always guard browser-only APIs
if (typeof window !== 'undefined') {
    window.scrollTo(0, 0);
}

// ✅ For React effects, useEffect only runs in browser
useEffect(() => {
    document.title = 'Hello';  // Safe — useEffect is browser-only
}, []);
```

APIs that require guards: `window`, `document`, `navigator`, `localStorage`,
`sessionStorage`, `location`, `history`, `alert`, `confirm`, `prompt`,
`requestAnimationFrame`, `IntersectionObserver`, `ResizeObserver`, `MutationObserver`.

## TypeScript — No 'any' Type

Never use `any`. It defeats TypeScript's purpose and hides bugs that surface in production.

```tsx
// ❌ Lazy — hides type errors
const data: any = response.data;
function handleClick(e: any) { ... }
const items = props.items as any[];

// ✅ Define interfaces for everything
interface ArticleResponse {
    id: string;
    title: string;
    body: string;
    published_at: string | null;
}

const data: ArticleResponse = response.data;
function handleClick(e: React.MouseEvent<HTMLButtonElement>) { ... }
```

When the type is genuinely uncertain, use `unknown` with type guards:
```tsx
function parseResponse(data: unknown): Article {
    if (typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && 'title' in data) {
        return data as Article;
    }
    throw new Error('Invalid article data');
}
```

Use `import type` for type-only imports:
```tsx
import type { Article, Category } from '@/types';
import { formatDate } from '@/utils/date';
```

## Navigation — Inertia Link vs <a>

This is a Single Page Application. Using `<a>` for internal links causes full page reloads,
destroys client state, and breaks the SPA experience.

```tsx
// ❌ Full page reload — kills SPA state, flashes white, loses form data
<a href="/dashboard">Dashboard</a>
<a href={`/articles/${article.id}`}>Read More</a>

// ✅ Inertia SPA navigation — smooth, preserves state
import { Link } from '@inertiajs/react';
<Link href="/dashboard">Dashboard</Link>
<Link href={`/articles/${article.id}`}>Read More</Link>

// ✅ External links — these correctly use <a>
<a href="https://facebook.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
    Facebook
</a>
```

**Rule of thumb:** If the URL starts with `/` it's internal → use `<Link>`.
If it starts with `http` it's external → use `<a target="_blank">`.

## Accessibility — REQUIRED, Not Optional

Every interactive element needs an accessible name. Screen readers and automated
testing tools (including our own SiteHealth scanner) flag these as errors.

```tsx
// ❌ No accessible name — screen reader says "button"
<button onClick={toggleMenu}>☰</button>
<button onClick={handleSearch}><SearchIcon /></button>
<input type="text" placeholder="Search..." />

// ✅ Accessible
<button onClick={toggleMenu} aria-label="Toggle navigation menu">☰</button>
<button onClick={handleSearch} aria-label="Search articles"><SearchIcon /></button>
<label htmlFor="site-search" className="sr-only">Search articles</label>
<input id="site-search" type="text" placeholder="Search..." />
```

Requirements:
- Icon-only buttons: MUST have `aria-label`
- Toggle buttons: MUST have `aria-label` AND `role="switch"` with `aria-checked`
- Form inputs: MUST have associated `<label>` (visible or `sr-only`) or `aria-label`
- Images: MUST have `alt` text (empty `alt=""` only for decorative images)
- Modals: MUST have `role="dialog"` and `aria-labelledby` pointing to the title

## Multi-App Branding — NEVER HARDCODE

This codebase renders multiple apps. The footer, header, social links, copyright,
and any brand-specific content MUST come from Inertia shared props, not hardcoded strings.

```tsx
// ❌ BRANDING LEAK — This will show "Go Event City" on Day.News
<footer>
    <p>© 2026 Go Event City. All rights reserved.</p>
    <a href="https://facebook.com/goeventcity">Facebook</a>
</footer>

// ✅ Dynamic — renders correctly for whichever app is running
const { footerConfig } = usePage().props;
<footer>
    <p>{footerConfig.copyright}</p>
    {footerConfig.social.map(link => (
        <a key={link.name} href={link.url} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
           aria-label={`${footerConfig.appName} on ${link.name}`}>
            {link.name}
        </a>
    ))}
</footer>
```

**NEVER put these strings directly in component files:**
- App names: "Day.News", "GoEventCity", "DowntownGuide", "GoLocalVoices", "AlphaSite"
- Social media URLs for specific apps
- Copyright text
- App-specific navigation links
- App-specific taglines or descriptions

All of these come from `usePage().props` which is populated by the middleware.

## Debug Code — Remove Before Commit

Never commit:
- `console.log()`, `console.debug()`, `console.info()` (console.warn and console.error are OK)
- `debugger` statements
- Commented-out code blocks longer than 3 lines
- `// TODO` items that reference the current task (finish them or create a ticket)

## Component Patterns

### Props: Always type explicitly
```tsx
interface ArticleCardProps {
    article: Article;
    onBookmark?: (id: string) => void;
    className?: string;
}

export default function ArticleCard({ article, onBookmark, className }: ArticleCardProps) {
```

### Events: Use specific types, not 'any'
```tsx
// ❌
const handleChange = (e: any) => { ... }

// ✅
const handleChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => { ... }
const handleSubmit = (e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) => { ... }
const handleClick = (e: React.MouseEvent<HTMLButtonElement>) => { ... }
```

### Buttons: Always specify type
```tsx
// ❌ Defaults to type="submit" — causes unexpected form submissions
<button onClick={handleClick}>Click Me</button>

// ✅ Explicit type prevents accidental form submission
<button type="button" onClick={handleClick}>Click Me</button>
```

## Import Hygiene

Remove unused imports. Every import must be used.

```tsx
// ❌ useState and useCallback imported but only useState is used
import { useState, useEffect, useCallback } from 'react';

// ✅ Only import what you use
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
```

## File Naming

- Pages: `PascalCase.tsx` matching the Inertia route (e.g., `resources/js/Pages/Articles/Index.tsx`)
- Components: `PascalCase.tsx` (e.g., `ArticleCard.tsx`)
- Utilities: `camelCase.ts` (e.g., `formatDate.ts`)
- Types: `camelCase.ts` in a `types/` directory (e.g., `types/article.ts`)
- Hooks: `useCamelCase.ts` (e.g., `useArticles.ts`)
